Wednesday August 28th 2013 9:41 am -04:00,The order of the statements is really important. At the point when the second assignment statement (<code>x = abs(x)</code>) is executed the value that <code>x</code> refers to is <code>10</code>. Therefore <code>y</code> refers to <code>10</code>. When the third assignment statement is executed the value that <code>x</code> refers to changes to <code>11</code> but <code>y</code> is not impacted by this change.It may help to trace this code in the Python Visualizer (see the Resources page)., Unresolved,0
Wednesday August 28th 2013 9:48 am -04:00,Here is the result of executing that code in the Python shell:<pre>>>> print(a b c sep=  end=)a b c>>> print(a b c sep= )a b c>>><pre>Notice that in the second line the prompt (>>>) appears right after the c. That is because the end parameter refers to the empty string. In the 2nd print function call a newline character (<code></code>) is used as the default end character so there is a newline after the c and the prompt appears on the next line., Resolved,0
